    {
      "id": "2PTkiViJrVMsgdvTG-H8U",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 324,
      "y": 1423,
      "width": 1252.259033203125,
      "height": 700,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 574109059,
      "version": 1567,
      "versionNonce": 1204680237,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1773900109543,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "WorkFlow :\nA message has following things :\nKey - string id\nValue - actual message\nPartition\nTopic - In which topic you want to publish\n\n(i) Producer creates a message, with key and value and topic. If partition is defined it will put message to that partn.\n(ii) If Partition and topic are empty then it will go to partition in round robin\n(iii) Offset will tell till where the consumer has read the message. Committed offset means the offset till it is read.\nZookeeper keeps tracks of this.\n(iv) Consumer group has consumers\n(v) Kafka cluster will have brokers, these brokers will have a leader but partitions will have replicas other brokers. If one\npartition goes down then replicas takeover. But all read and writes are done on main copy only. \n(vi) When a queue goes down nothing will happen, follower takes place of leader.\n(vii) When consumer goes down other consumer will take its place.\n(viii) When consumer is not able to process the message, it tries to retry and if retry also then it will be put to debt queue.\n\n\nDifference between Kafka is it is Pull based approach and RabbitMQ is push based approach.\n\n\n2) Rabbit MQ :\nIt is similar to kafka. But it has exchange and queues, if message is not processed then we can requeue it and there\nis no concept of offset here.\nDifferent types of exchange are :\n- Fan-out exchange\n- Direct exchange",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 1,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "baseline": 693,
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "WorkFlow :\nA message has following things :\nKey - string id\nValue - actual message\nPartition\nTopic - In which topic you want to publish\n\n(i) Producer creates a message, with key and value and topic. If partition is defined it will put message to that partn.\n(ii) If Partition and topic are empty then it will go to partition in round robin\n(iii) Offset will tell till where the consumer has read the message. Committed offset means the offset till it is read.\nZookeeper keeps tracks of this.\n(iv) Consumer group has consumers\n(v) Kafka cluster will have brokers, these brokers will have a leader but partitions will have replicas other brokers. If one\npartition goes down then replicas takeover. But all read and writes are done on main copy only. \n(vi) When a queue goes down nothing will happen, follower takes place of leader.\n(vii) When consumer goes down other consumer will take its place.\n(viii) When consumer is not able to process the message, it tries to retry and if retry also then it will be put to debt queue.\n\n\nDifference between Kafka is it is Pull based approach and RabbitMQ is push based approach.\n\n\n2) Rabbit MQ :\nIt is similar to kafka. But it has exchange and queues, if message is not processed then we can requeue it and there\nis no concept of offset here.\nDifferent types of exchange are :\n- Fan-out exchange\n- Direct exchange",
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    }
  ],
